data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9 (.NET 9), the Cosmos DB provider started **blocking synchronous I/O by default** because the underlying Cosmos SDK is async-only — sync calls were just doing `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` internally (risking deadlocks). An opt-in (`AllowSynchronousIO`) was provided as a temporary bridge.

**In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed.** All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider will throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

### The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return `Task<T>` / `Task`, mark methods `async`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

You'll also need to remove the `AllowSynchronousIO` configuration from your `DbContext` setup since the option no longer exists and will cause a compile error.
